ro}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|maisteri}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|მაგისტრი}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|मास्टर|m}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|magister}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|修士|tr=しゅうし, shūshi}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|магистр}}\n* Lao: {{t|lo|ມະຫາບັນດິດ}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t+|mn|магистр}}\n* Persian:\n*: Iranian Persian: {{t|fa|کارْشِناسِ اَرْشَد}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|magister|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|mestre}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|маги́стр|m}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|magister|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{t+|tl|pantas}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|มหาบัณฑิต}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|магі́стр|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|original of a document or of a recording}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|оригина́л|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|alkuperäinen}}, {{t|fi|alkuperäiskappale}}, {{t|fi|kantakappale}}, {{t|fi|kantakopio}}, {{t|fi|master-versio}}, {{t|fi|master-kopio}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|πρωτότυπο|n}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|असली}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|master}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|master|m}}, {{t+|it|originale|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|原本|tr=げんぽん, genpon}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|dominus|m}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|original|m}}, {{t|nb|masterkopi|m}}\n* Persian:\n*: Iranian Persian: {{t+|fa|اصلی|tr=asli}}\n* Polish: {{t|pl|kopia-matka|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|máster|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|original|n}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|оригина́л|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|maestro|m}} {{qualifier|recording}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|förlaga|c}}\n* Thai: {{t+|th|ต้นฉบับ}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|prif gopi|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|film: primary wide shot of a scene}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|legal: parajudicial officer}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t|cmn|聆案官}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|engineering: device that is controlling other devices or is an authoritative source}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|master|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|マスター|tr=masutā}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|веду́щий|m}}, {{t|ru|[[ведущий|веду́щее]] [[устро́йство]]|n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|freemasonry: person holding an office of authority}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|majstro}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|mestari}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|person holding a similar office in other civic societies}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t-needed|bg}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|puheenjohtaja}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|principale|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Latin: {{t+check|la|dominus|m}}\n* Turkish: {{t+check|tr|ağa}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n=====See also=====\n* {{l|en|journeyman}}\n* {{l|en|apprentice}}\n\n====Adjective====\n{{en-adj|-}}\n\n# [[masterful|Masterful]].\n#: {{ux|en|a '''master''' performance}}\n# [[main|Main]], [[principal]] or [[predominant]].\n# Highly [[skilled]].\n#: {{ux|en|'''master''' batsman}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1895|author=Marshall Mather|title=Lancashire Idylls|page=39\n|passage=In another minute she lay peaceful and motionless under the anæsthetic — a statue, immobile, yet expressionful, as though carved by some '''master''' hand.}}\n# Original.\n#: {{ux|en|'''master''' copy}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|en|master chief petty officer|master eye|master gunnery sergeant|master joint|master reset|master seaman|master shot|master spirit|master stock|masterstroke|master vibrator|master chief warrant officer|master warrant officer}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|main, principal or predominant}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|главен}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|pää-}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|κύριος}}, {{t+|el|κεντρικός}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|maestro}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|господарски}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|hoved-}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|highly skilled}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|майсторски}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|mestari|alt=-mestari}}, {{t+|fi|taituri|alt=-taituri}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|उस्ताद}}, {{t+|hi|माहिर}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|уста}}, {{t+|ky|чебер}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|мајсторски}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|mester-}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|استاد|tr=ostâd}}, {{t+|fa|ماهر|tr=mâher}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|majstorski}}, {{t|sh|мајсторски}}\n* Tajik: {{t+|tg|устод}}\n* Thai: {{t|th|ชั้นครู}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|original}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|оригинален}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|alkuperäinen}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|αυθεντικός}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|अस्ल}}, {{t+|hi|असल}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|mastro|m}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|[[original]]-}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|اصل|tr=asl}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To be a [[#Noun|master]].{{attention|en|highly ambiguous, master in what sense?}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To become the [[#Noun|master]] of; to subject to one's will, control, or authority; to conquer; to overpower; to subdue.\n#* {{RQ:Locke Education\n|passage=Obstinacy and willful neglects must be '''mastered''', even though it cost blows.}}\n#* {{RQ:Falkner Moonfleet|year=1934|passage=Then Elzevir cried out angrily, 'Silence. Are you mad, or has the liquor '''mastered''' you? Are you Revenue-men that you dare shout and roister? or contrabandiers with the lugger in the offing, and your life in your hand. You make noise enough to wake folk in Moonfleet from their beds.'}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[learn]] to a high degree of [[proficiency]].\n#: {{ux|en|It took her years to '''master''' the art of needlecraft.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To own; to possess.\n#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Merchant of Venice|V|i|183|2|{{...}}the wealth&nbsp;/ That the world '''maſters'''.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive|especially of a musical performance}} To make a [[#Adjective|master]] copy of.\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|usually with ''in''}} To earn a Master's degree.\n#: {{ux|en|He '''mastered''' in English at the state college.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|title=Terms derived from the verb ''master''\n|bemaster\n|masterable\n|overmaster\n|overmasteringly\n|remaster\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to be a master}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|господарствам}}, {{t+|bg|господствам}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|hallita}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|κυριαρχώ}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|господари|m}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|lede}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|stăpâni}}\n* Serbo-Croatian: {{t+|sh|gospodariti}}, {{t|sh|господарити}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to control}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|владея}}, {{t+|bg|управлявам}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|controleren}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|hallita}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|κυβερνώ}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|padroneggiare}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|владее}}, {{t|mk|управува}}, {{t|mk|раководи}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|styre}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|stăpâni}}, {{t+|ro|conduce}}, {{t+|ro|controla}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|ceannsaich}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|gwastrodi}}, {{t|cy|meistroli}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to learn to a high degree}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|овладявам|impf}}, {{t|bg|овладея|pf}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|beheersen}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|ellerni}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|hallita}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|maîtriser}}\n* German: {{t+|de|meistern}}, {{t+|de|beherrschen}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|κατέχω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|κρατέω}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|elsajátít}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|maasteroittaa}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|マスターする|tr=masutā suru}}, {{t+|ja|熟達|alt=熟達する|tr=jukutatsu suru}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|меңгеру}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|владее}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|mestre}}, {{t+|no|beherske}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|dominar}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|stăpâni}}, {{t+|ro|excela}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|dominar}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|bemästra}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t|uk|опано́вувати|impf}}, {{t|uk|опанува́ти|pf}}, {{t|uk|оволодіва́ти|impf}}, {{t|uk|оволоді́ти|pf}}, {{t|uk|засво́ювати|impf}}, {{t|uk|засво́їти|pf}}, {{t|uk|осво́ювати|impf}}, {{t|uk|осво́їти|pf}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to make a master copy of}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+check|bg|записвам|impf}}, {{t+check|bg|запиша|pf}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|masteritzar}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|masteroida}}\n* German: {{t|de|mastern}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|masterizar}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|meistroli}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{ety|en|id=vessel|:af|mast|-er<id:measurement>|text=+|tree=1}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|nautical|in combination}} A [[vessel]] having a specified number of [[mast]]s.\n#: {{ux|en|a two-'''master'''}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|four-master}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|vessel having specified number of masts}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|-мачтов|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t|fi|-mastoinen}} {{qualifier|in compound words}}\n* Polish: {{t|pl|-masztowiec|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aemrst|Stamer|ramset|metras|matres|mastre|maters|armets|armest|termas|tamers|trémas|remast|Tamers|Stream|ramets|'maters|stream|METARs|tremas|Amster}}\n\n{{cln|en|male equivalent nouns|terms of address}}\n{{C|en|Artists|People|Slavery}}\n\n==Finnish==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{bor|fi|en|master}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{fi-p}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|fi|noun}}\n\n# {{label|fi|BDSM}} (male) [[dom]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{fi-decl-paperi|master|a|i=0}}\n\n==French==\n{{wp|fr:}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|fr|en|master}}. {{doublet|fr|maestro}}, borrowed from Italian, {{m|fr|magister}}, borrowed from Latin, and {{m|fr|maître}}, inherited from Latin.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA|mastère|masteur}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Exilexi-master.wav}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Lepticed7-master.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Toulouse>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-master.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-master.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fr-noun|m}}\n\n# [[master's degree]], [[master's]] (postgraduate degree)\n# {{l|en|master}} (golf tournament)\n# {{l|en|master}}, [[master copy]]\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|en|trames}}, {{l|en|trémas}}\n\n==Indonesian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{dercat|id|nl|en|enm|ang|la|itc-ola|ine-pro}}\nFrom {{bor|id|nl|master}}. {{doublet|id|maestro|magister|mester}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{id-pr}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{id-noun|head=mastêr|a}}\n\n# {{l|en|master}} {{gl|someone who has control over something or someone}}\n#: {{syn|id|tuan}}\n# {{l|en|master}} {{gl|an expert at something}}\n#: {{syn|id|ahli}}\n# {{l|en|master}} {{gl|the original of a document or of a recording}}\n# {{lb|id|education}} {{l|en|master}} {{gl|a type of postgraduate degree, usually undertaken after a bachelor degree}}\n#: {{syn|id|magister|sarjana utama}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|id|verb|head=mastêr|active|memaster|passive|dimaster}}\n\n# to {{l|en|master}} {{gl|to learn to a high degree}}\n# to {{l|en|master}} {{gl|to make a master copy of}}\n\n====Affixed terms====\n{{col|id\n|masteran<t:the result of mastering>\n|masterkan<t:to master>\n|pemaster<t:masterer>\n|pemasteran<t:mastering>\n}}\n\n====Compounds====\n{{col|id\n|master internasional<t:International Master>\n}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:KBBI Daring}}\n\n{{cln|id|transitive verbs}}\n\n==Norwegian Bokmål==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|nb|noun form|g=m|g2=f}}\n\n# {{inflection of|nb|mast||indef|p}}\n\n==Norwegian Nynorsk==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{bor|nn|en|master}}. {{doublet|nn|magister}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-m1}}\n\n# a [[master's degree]]\n# a [[master's thesis]]\n# a person that has a master's degree\n# [[original]] [[document]] or [[recording]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n\n====Noun====\n{{nn-noun-irreg|f|mastra|ds2=mastri|mastrer|mastrene}}\n\n# {{nn-former|mast|2012}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|nn|nounf|g=f}}\n\n# {{infl of|nn|mast||indef|pl}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:nn:OB}}\n\n==Old Frisian==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alter|ofs|mēster}}\n* {{alter|ofs|māstere|mēstere}}\n\n===Etymology===\nBorrowed from {{bor|ofs|la-vul|*maester}}, from {{der|ofs|la|magister}}. Cognates include {{cog|ang|mæġester}} and {{cog|osx|mēstar}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ofs|/ˈmaːster/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{ofs-noun|m|head=māster}}\n\n# {{l|en|master}}\n# [[leader]]\n# [[commissioner]]\n\n====Inflection====\n{{ofs-decl-noun-a-m|māster}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|ofs|Māster}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|stq|Mäster}}\n* {{desc|fy|master}}\n\n====References====\n* {{R:ofs:Bremmer:2009|page=28}}\n\n==Romanian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|ro|en|master}}. {{doublet|ro|măiestru|maestru|maistru|magistru|meșter}}.\n\n===Noun===\n{{ro-noun|m|mastere}}\n\n# [[master's degree]]\n\n====Declension====\n{{ro-noun-m|pl=mastere}}\n\n==Swedish==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|sv|noun form}}\n\n# {{noun form of|sv|mast||indef|p}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|sv|a=aemrst|smarte|smetar}}\n\n==Turkish==\n{{wp|tr:Yüksek lisans}}\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{alt|tr|mastır}}\n\n===Etymology===\n{{bor+|tr|en|master}}, from {{der|tr|ang|mæġester}}, from {{der|tr|la|magister}}, from {{der|tr|ine-pro|*méǵh₂s}}. {{doublet|tr|maestro}}. \n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|tr|/ˈmas.tɯɾ/}}\n* {{hyph|tr|mas|ter}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{tr-noun|ı|lar}}\n\n# [[master's degree]]\n#: {{syn|tr|yüksek lisans}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:tr:TDK}}\n* {{R:tr:Nişanyan}}\n* {{R:lugatim}}\n\n==West Frisian==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{rfe|fy}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fy-noun|c|masters|masterke}}\n\n# [[#English|master]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|fy|boargemaster}}\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{R:WFT|61508}}"}}